"CIA OFFICER ON PLOT TO KILL LUMUMBA 

January 17 marks 65 years since the assassination of Patrice Lumumba, the Democratic Republic of Congoâ€™s first democratically elected prime minister and one of Africaâ€™s most powerful independence leaders. Lumumbaâ€™s death remains one of the darkest and most consequential episodes in Congolese and African history.

Lumumba came to power in 1960 as the DRC emerged from brutal Belgian colonial rule. A fierce advocate of national sovereignty, pan-African unity and self-determination, he challenged Western control over Congoâ€™s vast resources and refused to be politically subservient. As a result he was overthrown and imprisoned in a coup by army chief Joseph Mobutu backed by Belgium and the US only a few months after taking power. 

Lumumba was later tortured and executed by a Katangan firing squad under the supervision of Belgian officers. To erase his legacy, his body was dismembered and dissolved in acid, leaving no grave that could become a site of resistance. In 2022, Belgium returned a single tooth, the only remaining part of his body, to his family for burial in Kinshasa.

The clip referenced here comes from the documentary Inside the CIA: On Company Business. In it, former CIA officer John Stockwell alleges that CIA station chief Larry Devlin had been involved in plans to poison Lumumba, before a military coup was ultimately chosen as the preferred method of removal. The interview offers a rare, chilling insight into the covert operations and foreign interference that sealed Lumumbaâ€™s fate and reshaped the future of the Congo.

Lumumbaâ€™s story is indeed telling of the malicious nature of foreign powers and how they suppressed post-independence Pan-African movements across the continent. But much like Nkrumah and Sankara, Lumumbaâ€™s ideas lived on and continue to inspire revolutionaries around the world.

